<section xml:id="recursion-summary">
  <title>Recursion Summary</title><introduction>
    
    <p>In this unit you learned about <term>recursion</term>.  A recursive method calls itself (contains a call to the method from inside of the method).  A recursive method should have at least one way to stop the recursion.  This is called a base case.</p>
    <idx>recursion</idx>

  </introduction>
  <subsection xml:id="concept-summary-index-0-6">
            <title>Concept Summary</title>
            <p><ul>
                <li>
                    <p><term>base case</term> - A way to stop the recursive calls. This is a return without a recursive call.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p><term>call stack</term> - The call stack keeps track of the methods that are called while the code executes. It keeps track of the local variables and where the call will return to.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p><term>recursive method</term> - A method that contains at least one call to itself inside the method.</p>
                </li>
            </ul></p>
        </subsection>
